ration sets regardless of the incentive (i.e., Democratic counties) and (ii) consumers value cost-saving more (i.e., counties with lower middle income). Also, the heightened demand for PHEVs following the incentive stems from the substitution from gasoline vehicles with high fuel efficiency. We estimate the average cost of reducing carbon emissions through tax credits to be $109 per ton, which is less expensive than tax rebates for conventional hybrids and subsidies for residential solar panels.This paper was accepted by David Simchi-Levi, Special Section of Management Science on Business and Climate Change.Supplemental Material: The online appendix and data are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2023.4781.
